This notebook will visualise the estimated dominant frequencies over a spectrogram. I'd like to see if I can tell the origin of the dominant frequencies clearly. The issue with the dominant frequency paradigm is that many things can get picked up:

  • CF peak frequencies
  • Doppler shifted reflections of the CF peak frequencies
  • Reverberations

original notebook date: 15-11-2020

author: Thejasvi Beleyur

# find matched audio
randrow = np.random.choice(len(virtual_split_measure['file_name']),1)
fname = virtual_split_measure['file_name'][int(randrow)]
matched_audio = cca.find_file_in_folder(fname,'../')
audio, fs = sf.read(matched_audio[0])
# split into windows 
audio_segs = split_measure.split_audio(audio, fs, 0.05)
# visualise spectrogram 

available_segnums = np.unique(virtual_split_measure[virtual_split_measure['file_name']==fname]['segment_number']) #int(np.random.choice(range(len(audio_segs)),1))
rand_segnum = np.random.choice(available_segnums, 1)
current_seg = audio_segs[int(rand_segnum)]
plt.specgram(current_seg, Fs=fs, NFFT=500, noverlap=480);

# overlay dominant frequencies
byseg_filename = virtual_split_measure.groupby(['file_name','segment_number','measurement'])
df = byseg_filename.get_group((fname,int(rand_segnum),'dominant_frequencies'))

# save into spectrogram images 
for each in df['value']:
    plt.hlines(each, 0, current_seg.size/fs, linewidth=0.5, label=str(each))
plt.legend()
plt.ylim(80000,125000)

# Observed audio 



# find matched audio
randfile = np.random.choice(verif_annots['valid_annotations'],1) + '_hp.WAV'
audio_folder = '../../individual_call_analysis/hp_annotation_audio/'
file_path = cca.find_file_in_folder(randfile, audio_folder)[0]

audio, fs = sf.read(file_path)
# split into windows 
audio_segs = split_measure.split_audio(audio[:,0], fs, 0.05)
# visualise spectrogram 

available_segnums = np.unique(obs_split_measure[obs_split_measure['file_name']==randfile[0]]['segment_number'])
rand_segnum = int(np.random.choice(available_segnums, 1))
current_seg = audio_segs[rand_segnum]
plt.figure()
plt.specgram(current_seg, Fs=fs, NFFT=500, noverlap=480);

# overlay dominant frequencies
byseg_filename = obs_split_measure.groupby(['file_name','segment_number','measurement'])
df = byseg_filename.get_group((randfile[0],rand_segnum,'dominant_frequencies'))

# save into spectrogram images 
for each in df['value']:
    plt.hlines(each, 0, current_seg.size/fs, linewidth=0.5, label=str(each))
plt.legend()
plt.ylim(80000,125000)

In [41]:
all_multibatfiles = np.unique(obs_split_measure[obs_split_measure['num_bats']>1]['file_name'])
file_rms = pd.DataFrame(data={'filename': all_multibatfiles, 'max_ch_dbrms':np.nan})
for i,multibatfile in enumerate(all_multibatfiles):
    audio_folder = '../../individual_call_analysis/hp_annotation_audio/'
    file_path = cca.find_file_in_folder(multibatfile, audio_folder)[0]
    audio, fs = sf.read(file_path)
    file_rms.loc[i,'filename'] = multibatfile
    file_rms.loc[i, 'max_ch_dbrms'] = np.max([dB(audio[:,0]), dB(audio[:,1])])
